taly and challenge the idea that Florentine women had an inferior legal position and civic status.In Marriage, Dowry, and Citizenship in Late Medieval and Renaissance Italy, Kirshner collects nine important essays which address these issues in Florence and the cities of northern and central Italy. Using a cross-disciplinary approach that draws on the methodologies of both social and legal history, the essays in this collection present a wealth of examples of daughters, wives, and widows acting as full-fledged social and legal actors.Revised and updated to reflect current scholarship, the essays in Marriage, Dowry, and Citizenship in Late Medieval and Renaissance Italy appear alongside an extended introduction which situates them within the broader field of Renaissance legal history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipzItalyzFlorencexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aDowryzItalyzFlorencexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aLaw, Medieval. 0aMarriage lawzItalyzFlorencexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aReal propertyzItalyzFlorencexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aRenaissancezItalyzFlorence. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etczItalyzFlorencexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266451740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442664517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442664517.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles